<div id="comment_status_65026525" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_65026525" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_65026525" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_65026525" name="comment_link_65026525" href="//it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23556325&amp;cid=65026525" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(65026525)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_65026525" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65026525); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~fahrbot-bot">fahrbot-bot</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~fahrbot-bot">( 874524 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65026525"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65026525"><p><div class="quote"><p>Passkeys will be around until someone figures out a fatal and unrecoverable weakness with them.</p></div><p>
From TFA... not necessarily fatal or unrecoverable, but probably super annoying or problematic:</p><p><div class="quote"><p>Passkeys are not foolproof though. A compromised device might expose private keys, and a successful social engineering attack could dupe a user into creating a passkey for a malicious service.
</p><p>
There are also potential problems if the user loses access to a device that stores passkeys &ndash; another means of authenticating to a passkey-linked service would be required, which might involve passwords or a more involved recovery process.
</p><p>
Also, passkey portability between credential providers (across platforms or password manager applications) is still a work in progress.</p></div><p>
While it notes, "a compromised device might expose private keys" it fails to be clear that it might expose *all* your private keys.  I'm not a fan of having all my eggs in one basket.  Also, using bio-metrics to access your passkey means no, or less, legal protections from searches -- so use a long PIN, or password - oh, wait<nobr> <wbr></nobr>...</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65026525">

